        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Pittston Coal Company miners in Virginia might not have been incredulous on hearing that 10,000 Soviet miners died on the job between 1979 and 1989 (''U.S. and Soviet Miners Meet and Find Surprises,'' news article, Jan. 22) if they had reflected on some of the other figures that your article provides.</p>
        <p>While the number of on-the-job Soviet deaths may be eight times the figure for United States miners, Soviet miners so outnumber their American counterparts (2.5 million to 140,000, according to your figures), that the on-the-job death rate for United States miners is more than twice the Soviet rate: 1 out of 112, as against 1 out of 250.</p>
        <p>With so much remaining to be achieved in safety standards and enforcement, it is too bad that the Pittston miners have had to struggle so long simply to avoid being pushed backward.</p>
        <p>STEVE SELTZER</p>
        <p>New York, Jan. 24, 1990</p>
      </block>
